(9, 1, 2, 4, 'April', 'June', 'DST-V2I2P101', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/DST-V2I2P101', 'The Improvements of Cluster Head Optimization Problems in WSNs Using an Improved Node Selection Model ', 1, 12, '[\"T.Kiruthiga\", \"K.Vijayakumar\", \"M.Sutharsan\"]', '<p>WSNs are networks of tiny wireless sensors that track changes in environmental variables like pressure, temperature, humidity, and motion. In these networks, data is often transmitted from the source to the sink node through a gateway connected to sensor nodes. In a WSN, choosing a CH is a crucial choice that must be made to guarantee effective network operation. Choosing a CH wisely is essential for the network to run effectively and offer its consumers high-quality service. This work addresses the CH problem in WSN using a novel optimization approach and an improved node selection model (EENSA). The new system\'s effectiveness is evaluated regarding energy consumption, network lifetime, CH selection, power-aware routing, and throughput compared to the existing methods, Multi-Objective Genetic Algorithms (MOGA), and Gravitational Search Algorithm (GSA). As a result, our suggested technique improves throughput and network longevity while consuming less energy.</p>', '[\"WSN\",\"CH\",\"Energy-Efficiency\",\"Node selection\",\"Genetic algorithm\"]', '<p>[1]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Xing-Wei Xu et al., “Improved Fish Migration Optimization with the Opposition Learning Based on Elimination Principle for Cluster Head Selection,” <i>Wireless Networks</i>, vol. 28, no. 3, pp.&nbsp;1017-1038, 2022.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1007/s11276-022-02892-3\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Improved+Fish+Migration+Optimization+with+the+Opposition+Learning+Based+on+Elimination+Principle+for+Cluster+Head+Selection&am