&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p>[8]&nbsp;F Capra, and V. N. Mansfield, “The Tao of Physics,”&nbsp;<i>Physics Today</i>, vol. 29, no. 8, 1976.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=The+Tao+of+Physics&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p>[9]&nbsp;Stella Kramrisch, <i>The Hindu Temple</i>, Motilal Banarsidass Publication, vol. 1, 1976.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.mlbd.in/products/the-hindu-temple-2-vols-stella-kramrisch-9788120802223-8120802225\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[10]&nbsp;Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan, <i>The Principal Upanisads</i>, Humanity Books, 1992.</p>', '2023-02-11', '2023-02-24', '2023-03-23', '2023-03-31', 'uploads/LLL/volume-1/issue-1/LLL-V1I1P104.pdf', '2025-09-25 12:53:53', '2025-11-17 11:51:01', 'published'),
(41, 2, 5, 15, 'April', 'June', 'LLL-V1I1P105', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/LLL-V1I1P105', 'Realism in V.S. Naipaul\'s \"A Bend in the River\"', 27, 29, '[\"T. Antony Cruz\"]', '<p>Reality is a subject that has become a part of our life. Whether an individual desires or dislikes it, there is no complete removal of it. It is like one\'s own shadow, which is inseparable. One succeeds in evading it with clever methods. The farther one goes away, the closer one comes into contact with it. It is always wise to be with the facts of life. An individual tries his best to be away from it using several strategies. When he happens to encounter directly, he is unable to withstand the issues of life. It is good that one should ever be associated with it.</p>', '[\"Excellence\",\"Reality\",\"Determination\",\"Nothing\",\"Endeavors\",\"Knowledge\",\"Ideology\"]', '<p>[1] V. S. Naipaul, <i>A Bend in the River</i>, London: Picador, 1979.</p><p>[2] Thomas Nelson, <i>NKJV Holy Bible</i>,&nbsp;2015.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[3] Elaine Campbell, \"A Refinement of Rage: V.S. Naipaul\'s A Bend in the River,\" <i>World&nbsp;Literature Written in English, </i>vol. 18, no. 2, pp. 394-406, 1979.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1080/17449857908588618\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=A+Refinement+of+Rage%3A+V.S.+Naipaul%27s+A+Bend+in+the+River&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>][<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/17449857908588618?journalCode=rjpw19\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[4] Prescott, Lynda, \"\"Past and Present Darkness: Sources for VS Naipaul\'s\" A Bend in the River,\" M<i>odern Fiction&nbsp;Studies, </i>vol.&nbsp;30, no. 3, pp. 547-559, 1984.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Past+and+Present+Darkness%3A+Sources+for+VS+Naipaul%27s%22+A+Bend+in+the+River&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/26281248\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[5] Literary Theory and Criticism, 2020.&nbsp;[Online].&nbsp;Available: https://literariness.org/2020/07/13/analysis-of-v-s-naipauls-a-bend-in-the-river/</p><p>[6] Sara Mills, <i>Michel Foucault,</i> Noida, Brijbasi Art Press, 2004.</p><p>[7] Parama Sarkar, <i>Postcolonial Literatures</i>, Orient Blackswan,2016.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://orientblackswan.com/details?id=9788125062837\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[8] Dr. Ravi Kumar Mishra, \"Postcolonial Perspectives in V.S. Naipaul\'s A Bend in the River<i>,\" Journal of Higher Education and Research Society: A Refereed International, </i>vol. 4, no. 2, pp. 131-137, 2016.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://herso.org/vol-4-issue-2-oct-2016/\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[9] J.P. Stern, <i>On realism</i>, 1<sup>st</sup> Edition London: Routledge, 1973.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=On+realism&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.routledge.com/On-Realism/Stern/p/book/9780367721862\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[10] Bibhu Padhi, \"Naipaul on Naipaul and the Novel,\"&nbsp;<i>The </i><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Johns Hopkins University Press</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 30, no. 3, pp. 455–65, 1984.&nbsp;</span></p><p>[<a style=