(42, 2, 5, 16, 'July', 'September', 'LLL-V1I2P101', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/LLL-V1I2P101', 'An Analysis of Symbolism and Metaphorical  Elements in The Book of Ecclesiastes: A Literary  Approach', 1, 7, '[\"T. Antony Cruz\", \"A. Sheba Edithna\"]', '<p>The study aims to analyse the symbolism and metaphorical themes through the book of Eccleciastes chapter 12 phrases. The author metaphorizes human life by representing nature and symbolically says man is the ultimate creation of the creator. The world was created only for the man to rule over. This interpretation of phrases and meanings is done by each verse of chapter 12 individually. Through this chapter, the ultimate aim of creation and the quest for existence are also analysed at the end of the article. Here, the metaphorical interpretations are made and analysed; the accurate meaning is undefined by the author. However, the theological scholars defined the metaphorical meanings according to the phrases built by the author, King Solomon. The first verse in chapter 12 helps to know the author’s intention to describe the upcoming verses and the last seven verses. Here, we can divide the first verse as an introduction of his insights, two to seven is a description of human life, and the last seven verses, eight to fourteen, talk about the in-depth truths to lead a life with care and some wise commandments and advice and the whole duty of man are drawn. Wholly the chapter is like a piece of advice to a son, a father who likes to give for his peaceful life on earth. From this, the interpretation is made of each verse, and the quest for existence is analysed from the work of art by the author or preacher, King Solomon.</p>', '[\"Creator\",\"Quest of existence\",\"Human life\",\"Metaphor\",\"Young days\",\"Imagery\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[1] The Holy Bible: King James Version, United States, 2004. [Online]. Available: https://www.google.co.in/books/edition/The_Holy_Bible/3EUgOyrQnmEC?hl=en&amp;gbpv=1&amp;dq=kjv+bible&amp;printsec=frontcover</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[2] Ecclesiastes 12, Bible Gateway. [Online]. Available:</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Ecclesiastes%2012&amp;version=KJV</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[3] Ecclesiastes 12, Bible Org. [Online]. Available: </span>https://bible.org/book/export/html/21121</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[4] Symbolism, Merriam-Webster. </span>[Online]. Available: https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/symbolism</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[5]F.F. Bruce, “The Wisdom Literature of the Bible: The Book of Ecclesiastes,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Biblical Studies</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 23, no. 4, pp. 144-148, 1952.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/bs/wisdom-7_bruce.pdf\">Publisher Link</a><span style=\"color:black;\">]</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[6] Ecclesiastes 12, Remember God in Your Youth, Bible Project. [Online]. Available: https://bibleproject.com/bible/amp/ecclesiastes/12/#:~:text=5Furthermore%2C%20they%20are%20afraid,the%20streets%</span><br><span style=\"color:black;\">20and%20market%20places</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[7] Ecclesiastes 12, Commentary, Bible Hub. [Online]. Available: </span>https://biblehub.com/commentaries/ecclesiastes/12.htm</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[8] Bálint Károly Zabán, “Metaphors in the Wisdom Literature of the Hebrew Bible and Contemporary Art,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Religions</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 7, no. 9, 2016.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.3390/rel7090106\">CrossRef</a><span style=\"color:black;\">] [</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Metaphors+in+the+Wisdom+Literature+of+the+Hebrew+Bible+and+Contemporary+Art&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a><span style=\"color:black;\">] [</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/7/9/106\">Publisher Link</a><span style=\"color:black;\">]</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[9] Ecclesiastes 12 Twelfth Chapter of the Biblical Book Ecclesiastes, Wikiwand. [Online]. Available: </span>https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Ecclesiastes_12</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[10] The Conclusion of the Matter (Eccleciastes Chapter 12), Christian Library, 2003. [Online]. Available: https://www.christianstudylibrary.org/article/conclusion-matter</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '2023-06-30', '2023-07-25', '2023-09-08', '2023-09-26', 'uploads/LLL/volume-1/issue-2/LLL-V1I2P101.pdf', '2025-09-25 12:53:53', '2025-11-17 12:55:38', 'published'),
(43, 2, 5, 16, 'July', 'September', 'LLL-V1I2P102', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/LLL-V1I2P102', 'Social Influence and Anxiety of Modern Society on Man in the Selected Novels of Franz Kafka: A Study', 8, 12, '[\"R. Shakthi Vikram\", \"S. Saransri\", \"F. Flora Jannet\"]', '<p>This paper focussed on the influence of society on man and how it leads to anxiety. Kafka’s protagonists are Gregor, Josef K, and Mr. Klamm, taken for this study to compare their anxiety to modern-day people’s anxiety. As Kafka prophesizes through his deep-suffering characters, suggestions are made to throw anxiety naturally in this post-modern era. The clinical diagnosis reports analyse the social influence to compare the modern struggles people face and Kafka’s protagonists. Everything will be the same; the anxiety of man is always alarming the upcoming disaster, it may be family or society. Maybe Kafka is the mouthpiece of society and the forthcoming war society. So, throughout his characters, it is proven that lack of care and attention to self and others and voluntarily giving up one’s rights are man’s weaknesses and the first cause of the disaster. Thus, the study fully concentrates on today’s generation through Kafka’s protagonists. Various clinical diagnoses are compared, and solutions are analysed in this study.</p>', '[\"Depression\",\"Anxiety\",\"Society\",\"Influence\",\"Self-care\",\"Love\",\"Modern man.\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[1] <span style=\"color:black;\">Franz Kafka,</span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i> Metamorphosis</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">,</span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i> </i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">2014.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.google.co.in/books/edition/Metamorphosis/Ff2boAEACAAJ?hl=en&amp;bshm=rime/1\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[2] Willa Muir,&nbsp;and&nbsp;Franz Kafka, </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>The Castle</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">,&nbsp;United Kingdom,&nbsp;Minerva,&nbsp;1992.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[3] Willa Muir,&nbsp;and&nbsp;Franz Kafka, </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>The Trial</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, United Kingdom,&nbsp;Vintage,&nbsp;2005.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[4] <span style=\"color:black;\">Heta Yli-Länttä, “Young People’s Experiences of Social Fears,”&nbsp;</span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>International Journal of Adolescence and Youth</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 25, no. 1, pp. 1022-1035,&nbsp;2020.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1080/02673843.2020.1828110\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Young+People%E2%80%99s+Experiences+of+Social+Fears&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02673843.2020.1828110\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[5] Gitanjali Natarajan et al., “A Case Report of Psychotic Symptoms in Social Anxiety Disorder,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine,</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">&nbsp;vol. 41, no. 3, pp. 291-293, 2019.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.4103/IJPSYM.IJPSYM_275_18\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=A+Case+Report+of+Psychotic+Symptoms+in+Social+Anxiety+Disorder&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.4103/IJPSYM.IJPSYM_275_18\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[6] Franz Kafka, Critical Essays Understanding Kafka, The Trial. [Online]. Available: https://www.cliffsnotes.com/literature/t/the-trial/critical-essays/understanding-kafka#:~:text=One%20can%20also%20read%20The,horror%20of%20Nazism%20so%20convincingly.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[7] Naser Mrasori, and Naim Kryeziu, “Franc Kafka - Prophet of Modern Times Appreciations and Thoughts on His Creativity,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Journal of Language and Linguistic Studies</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 17, no. 3, pp. 1661-1668, 2021.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1177/004724418401405602\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Franc+Kafka+-+Prophet+of+modern+times+appreciations+and+thoughts+on+his+creativity&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.jlls.org/index.php/jlls/article/view/3570\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[8] W.J. Dodd, “Varieties of Influence: On Kafka’s Indebtedness to Dostoevskii,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Journal of European Studies</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 14, no. 56, pp. 257-269, 2016.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Varieties+of+Influence%3A+On+Kafka%27s+Indebtedness+to+Dostoevskii&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/004724418401405602\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[9] Walter H. Sokel, “Kafka as a Jew,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>New Literary History</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 30, no. 4, pp. 837-853, 1999.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Kafka+as+a+Jew&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.proquest.com/docview/221370758\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[10] Muhammad Azfar Nisar, and Ayesha Masood, “Dealing with Disgust: Street-Level Bureaucrats as Agents of Kafkaesque Bureaucracy,” </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Organisation</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, vol. 27, no. 6, 2019.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1177/1350508419883382\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Dealing+with+disgust%3A+Street-level+bureaucrats+as+agents+of+Kafkaesque+bureaucracy&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1350508419883382\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[11] Kafkatrap, Wiktionary. [Online]. Available: https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Kafkatrap&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '2023-06-30', '2023-07