p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[7] Rebecca J. Lukens, <i>A</i> <i>Critical Handbooks of Children’s Literature</i>, 5<sup>th</sup> ed, Harper Collins, 1995.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.amazon.in/Critical-Handbook-Childrens-Literature/dp/0673469379\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[8] Kathleen F. Malu, “Exploring Children’s Picture Story Books with Adult and Adolescent EFL Learners,” <i>English Teaching Forum</i>, vol. 51, no. 3, pp. 10-18, 2013. &nbsp;</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Exploring+children%E2%80%99s+picture+story+books+with+adult+and+adolescent+EFL+learners&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ1020720\">Publisher Link</a>]<span style=\"color:rgb(34,34,34);\">&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[9] Donna E. Norton, <i>Through the Eyes of a Child:</i> <i>An Introduction to Children\'s Literature</i>, 4<sup>th</sup> ed., Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Merrill, 1995. [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Norton%2C+D.+%281995%29.+Through+the+eyes+of+the+child.&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[10] Allan Paivio, <i>Mental Representations: A Dual Coding Approach,</i> Oxford University Press, 2008.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195066661.001.0001\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Mental+representations%3A+A+dual+coding+approach&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://academic.oup.com/book/10932\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[11] Sarah Phillips, <i>Young Learners, </i>Oxford UP, 1993.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=%5B11%5D%09Phillips%2C+S.+%281993%29.+Young+learners.+Oxford+UP.+&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p>[12]&nbsp;Matthew Rampley, <i>Exploring Visual Culture: Definition, Concepts, Contexts,</i> Edinburg University, 2005.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1515/9781474471879\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Exploring+visual+culture%3A+Definition%2C+concepts%2C+contexts&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.degruyter.com/document/doi/10.1515/9781474471879/html\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[13] Pam Schiller, <i>Seven Skills for School Success: Activities to Develop Social and Emotional Intelligence in Young Children</i>, Beltsville, Gryphon House, USA, 2009.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Seven+skills+for+school+success%3A+Activities+to+develop+social+and+emotional+intelligence+in+young+Children&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.iactivelearning.com/sites/default/files/book/samples/Pam_Schiller-Seven_Skills_for_School_Success-Sample.pdf\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>[14]&nbsp;Ellen Handler Spitz, <i>Inside Picture Books</i>, Yale University Press, 1999.</p><p>[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Inside+picture+books&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300084764/inside-picture-books/\">Publisher Link</a>]</p>', '2024-11-06', '2024-12-11', '2025-01-12', '2025-01-31', 'uploads/LLL/volume-3/issue-1/LLL-V3I1P101.pdf', '2025-09-25 12:53:57', '2025-11-17 12:55:38', 'published'),
(52, 2, 7, 22, 'January', 'March', 'LLL-V3I1P102', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/LLL-V3I1P102', 'Unintentional Animal Violence in Novel Engel’s Bear and Coetzee’s Disgrace', 9, 20, '[\"Prativa Poudel\"]', '<p>Although unintentional violence against nonhuman animals is far more pervasive and harder to detect and regulate than intentional violence, critics and animal rights activists have not paid sufficient attention to it, leaving the causes behind the unintentional violence unexplained. This research unearths the human domestication of nonhuman animals to be pivotal in that it camouflages unintended violence, and the philosophical underpinnings behind the domestication and its role in unintended violence are explained by analyzing the major instances of unintended violence to nonhuman animals in Marion Engel’s Bear and J. M. Coetzee’s Disgrace. It is hypothesized that unintentional violence escapes from human notice and acknowledgement largely because of human beings’ deep-rooted humanism, speciesism, anthropomorphism, and anthropocentrism, and ethics based on them underlies indirect duty, rationality, Cartesianism or automatism, human exceptionalism, animal instrumentalism, in isolation or combination.</p>', '[\"Unintended violence\",\"Nonhuman animal\",\"Cartesianism\",\"Human exceptionalism\",\"Animal instrumentalism.\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[1]&nbsp; Giorgio Agamben, <i>The Open: Man and Animal</i>, Stanford University Press, pp. 1-119, 2004.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=The+open%3A+Man+and+animal.+&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://books.google.co.in/books?hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;id=X8SIcG3I-W4C&amp;oi=fnd&amp;pg=PP9&amp;dq=The+open:+Man+and+animal.+&amp;ots=nPv7Na1J_3&amp;sig=GaHRWbbCSmsAaaPet2l1RTQdPDQ&amp;redir_esc=y#v=onepage&amp;q=The%20open%3A%20Man%20and%20animal.&amp;f=false\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[2] NuÌ ria Almiron, “Beyond Anthropocentrism: Critical Animal Studies and the Political Economy of Animal Exploitation,”&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>The Political Economy of Communication</i>, vol. 4, no. 2, pp. 17-30, 2016.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Beyond+anthropocentrism%3A+Critical+animal+studies+and+the+political+economy+of+animal+exploitation&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.polecom.org/index.php/polecom/article/view/71\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[3] Aristotle, <i>Complete Works of Aristotle, Volume 2: The Revised Oxford Translation</i>, REV-Revised, Princeton University Press, 1985.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Complete+Works+of+Aristotle%2C+Volume+2%3A+The+Revised+Oxford+Translation&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.degruyterbrill.com/document/doi/10.1515/9781400835850/html\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[4] Matthew Calarco, and Peter Atterton, </span><em style=\"color:black;\"><i>Animal Philosophy: Essential Readings in Continental Thought</i></em><span style=\"color:black;\">, Continuum, 2004.</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Animal+philosophy%3A+Essential+readings+in+