(53, 2, 7, 22, 'January', 'March', 'LLL-V3I1P103', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/LLL-V3I1P103', 'Increasing Students’ Interest in the Lesson with the Support of the Teacher', 21, 26, '[\"Gunay Naghiyeva\"]', '<p>The article correctly defines the problem of effective ways for students to master learning techniques from a scientific and practical point of view. For this reason, the scientific and methodologically correct organization and guidance of effective ways for students to master learning techniques, both by teachers in the classroom and by parents at home, increases children’s interest in learning and opens up wide opportunities for them to be more skilled in their future lives. Each child must have certain sufficient reasons for studying. These reasons can be various. Attracting students to the lesson is very hard in an era of increasingly modern technological tools. The article practically explains these reasons, referring to vital facts and based on observations made on children during teaching practice. In conclusion, the article shows that if students’ reasons for studying are clear, their enthusiasm and interest in learning will increase, and their success rate will increase. Students` interest will be increased by a teacher using new ways of teaching.</p>', '[\"Active learning\",\"Correct organization of learning\",\"Effective ways\",\"Learning motive\",\"Learning techniques.\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[1] F. Sadigov, <i>Pedagogy</i>, Baku Business University, 2008.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=F.+Sadigov%2C+Pedagogy%2C+Baku+Business+University%2C+2008&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[2] A. Badalova, <i>Education and Upbringing</i>, Ministry of Education of the Republic of Azerbaijan, Baku. 2015.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[3]&nbsp;A. Gadirov, <i>Age Psychology</i>, Maarif Publishing House, Baku, 2002.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[4]&nbsp;Ismail Kurt, and Seyit Ali Tüz, <i>Family and Child Rearing in Islam</i>,” Istanbul, 2005.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[5]&nbsp;Pat Mesiti, <i>Dreams Never Sleep</i>, Sistem, Istanbul, 1998.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[6]&nbsp;Anton Semenovich Makarenko, <i>A Book for Parents</i>, 1937.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[7]&nbsp;Parul Agarwal, and Ishrat Naaz, “Teacher Development and Teacher Education,” <i>Journal of Indian Research</i>, vol. 8, no. 3-4, 2020.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Teacher+development+and+teacher+education%E2%80%9D%2C+Journal+of+Indian+research&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://jir.mewaruniversity.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Teacher%20Development%20and%20Teacher%20Education%20By%20Parul%20Agarwal%20and%20Dr.%20Ishrat%20Naaz.pdf\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[8]&nbsp;Keith G. Diem, and Judy Levings, “Making Learning Fun,” <i>UF Department of 4-H Youth Development</i>, vol. 2014, no. 7, pp. 1-5, 2014.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.32473/edis-4h340-2014\">CrossRef</a><span style=\"color:black;\">] [</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://ojs.test.flvc.org/edis/article/view/131690\">Publisher Link</a><span style=\"color:black;\">]</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[9]&nbsp;Sam Goundar, “The Distraction of Technology in the Classroom,” <i>Journal of Education &amp; Human Development</i>, vol. 3, no. 1, pp. 211-229, 2014.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=The+distraction+of+technology+in+the+classroom&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a><span style=\"color:black;\">] [</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://jehd.thebrpi.org/vol-3-no-1-march-2014-abstract-14-jehd\">Publisher Link</a><span style=\"color:black;\">]</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[10]Turkan Ismayilli, “Developing Students Verbal Communication Skills and Speech Etiquette in English Language Teaching,” <i>Scientific Work International Scientific Journal</i>, vol. 19, no. 1, pp. 22-26, 2025.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\"><span style=\"color:black;\">[</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=%5B10%5D%09T.+Ismayilli%2C+Developing+Students+Verbal+Communication+Skills+and+Speech+Etiquette+in+English+Language+Teaching%2C+2025&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a><span style=\"color:black;\">] [</span><a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.aem.az/uploads/posts/2025/01/E.%C4%B0.%2019.1-14-18.pdf\">Publisher Link</a><span style=\"color:black;\">]</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '2025-01-02', '2025-02-04', '2025-03-12', '2025-03-31', 'uploads/LLL/volume-3/issue-1/LLL-V3I1P103.pdf', '2025-09-25 12:53:58', '2025-11-17 11:51:01', 'published'),
(54, 2, 7, 23, 'April', 'June', 'LLL-V3I2P101', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/LLL-V3I2P101', 'Pronouns and Pronominalization in Ògè', 1, 12, '[\"Babatunde A. Abdullahi\"]', '<p>This research examines the morphology and syntax of pronouns in Ògè, a language spoken in Akoko, Ondo State, Nigeria. Ògè faces endangerment as younger generations increasingly code-mix with Yoruba. Pronouns, fundamental to most languages, replace nouns for fluency and avoid repetition. The data for this study is based on fieldwork in which Ògè equivalents for the Ibadan 400-word list were collected, as were translations of sentences from Yoruba. The native speakers aged between 50 and 80 years were purposively selected because they better master the speech form than the younger generation, who cannot speak the speech form without code-mixing and code-switching. The wordlist and the sentences were dictated to the informants, and their responses were recorded and transcribed for analysis. Findings revealed that Ògè exhibits various pronoun types, including personal, possessive, anaphoric, interrogative, and demonstrative pronouns. Unlike many languages, Ògè pronouns lack inflection for gender or animacy. However, they do have morphological inflection for cases (nominative, accusative, and genitive) depending on their syntactic position in a sentence. The analysis reveals distinct forms for subject and object pronouns. Notably, the third-person singular object pronoun is phonetically zero, replaced by a copy of the verb\'s vowel and a tonal shift. Similarly, the second-person singular and plural object pronouns share the same form. This research serves as a part of the documentation of an aspect of the syntax of Ògè.</p>', '[\"Anaphoric\",\"Reflexives\",\"Pronominalization\",\"Ògè.\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[1] Noam Chomsky, <i>Lectures on Government and Binding</i>,<i> </i>Foris Publications, 1981.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Lectures+on+Government+and+Binding&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[2] David Crystal, <i>Language Death,</i> Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2000.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Language+Death.+Cambridge%3A+Cambridge+University+Press.+&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://textos.pucp.edu.pe/pdf/287.pdf\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[3] Bernd Heine, and Hiroyuki Miyashita, <i>The intersection between reflexives and reciprocals: A grammaticalization perspective</i>, Reciprocals and Reflexives: Theoretical and Typological Exploration, pp. 169-224, New York: De Gruyter Mouton, 2008.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1515/9783110199147.169\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Intersection+between+Reflexives+and+Reciprocals%3A+A+Grammaticalization+Perspective.+&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.degruyterbrill.com/document/doi/10.1515/9783110199147.169/html\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[4] Ekkehard König, and Volker Gast, <i>Reciprocals and Reflexives: Theoretical and Typological Exploration</i>, Berlin, New York: De Gruyter Mouton, 2008.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1515/9783110199147\">CrossRef</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Reciprocals+and+Reflexives%3A+Theoretical+and+Typological+Exploration&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.degruyterbrill.com/document/doi/10.1515/9783110199147/html\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[5] Victor Manfredi, “Antilogophoricity as Domain Extension in Igbo and Yoruba,” <i>Niger-Congo Syntax and Semantics, </i>vol. 1<i>, </i>pp. 97-117, 1987.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Antilogophoricity+as+Domain+Extension+in+Igbo+and+Yoruba&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[6] Henk van Riemsdijk, and Edwin Williams, <i>Introduction to the Theory of Grammar</i>, MIT Press, 1986.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Riemsdijk%2C+H.+C.%2C+%26+Williams%2C+E.+%281986%29.+Introduction+to+the+Theory+of+Grammar.+Cambridge%2C+MA%3A+The+MIT+Press.Sells%2C+P.+%281987%29.+Aspects+of+Logophoricity.+Linguistic+Inquiry%2C+18%2C+445-481.&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[7] Herbert Stahlke, “Pronouns and Islands in Yorùbá,” <i>Studies in African Linguistics, </i>vol. 5, no. 2, pp. 171-204, 1974.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Pronouns+and+Islands+in+Yor%C3%B9b%C3%A1.+Studies+in+African+Linguistics%2C+&amp;btnG=\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a style=\"color:rgb(0, 176, 80);\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" href=\"https://www.proquest.com/openview/442d8f34676d3b43a815209eea6ddbaa/1?cbl=1817060&amp;pq-origsite=gscholar\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '2025-02-07', '2025-03-06', '2025-04-07', '2025-04-30', 'uploads/LLL/volume-3/issue-2/LLL-V3I2P101.pdf', '2025-09-25 12:53:58', '2025-11-17 11:51:01', 'published');
