(149, 6, 18, 56, 'July', 'September', 'DSM-V1I3P101', 'https://doi.org/10.59232/DSM-V1I3P101', 'Nutritional Properties of Some Selected Microorganisms on ‘Otika’, a Nigerian Fermented Beverage', 1, 11, '[\"Oriola\", \"Olasunkanmi Bukola\"]', '“Otika” is a fermented grain beverage made in the Southwestern region of Nigeria using locally developed fermentation methods. On the third day of fermentation, it has a nice flavor that is sweet, somewhat sour, and has an opaque brown color. This work aims to assess the nutritional properties of this beverage by using a few chosen predominant microorganisms, both in a mixed and single form. An analysis of this fermented beverage’s proximate, antinutrient and mineral content was done. After 72 hours of fermentation, the pH dropped from 7.2 to 4.9, and the total titratable acid increased from 0.04% to 0.1%. When compared to other isolates, L. plantarum had the greatest protein content (1.33 ± 0.05%). Wesiella cibaria had the lowest carbohydrate amount (8.24 ±0.6%), whereas S. cerevisiae had the greatest carbohydrate content (11.02 ± 0.02%). The W. cibaria culture yielded the lowest levels of tannin and total phenol content (1.9± 0.0 mg/100g and 2.5± 0.00 mg/100g, respectively). The values of potassium, magnesium, iron, and zinc with the Otika bought from a local producer were the highest at 18.26 ± 0.02, 2.03 ±0.11, 0.42 ±0.14, and 2.02 ± 0.01 mg/100g, respectively. Overall, the use of the W.cibaria strain as a single starter culture in the fermentation process of “Otika” helped to raise the nutritive value among other microorganisms that served as starter cultures.', '[\"Mineral content\",\"Proximate composition\",\"Fermentation\",\"Starter culture\",\"Anti nutrient.\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[1] Kolawole O.M., Kayode R.M.O., and Akinduyo B., “Proximate and Microbial Analyses of “Burukutu” and “Pito” Produced in Ilorin, Nigeria,” <em>African Journal of Biotechnology</em>, vol. 6, no. 5, pp. 587-590, 2007. </p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Proximate+and+microbial+analyses+of+%E2%80%9CBurukutu%E2%80%9D+and+%E2%80%9CPito%E2%80%9D+produced+in+Ilorin%2C+Nigeria&amp;btnG=\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\" previewlistener=\"true\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a href=\"https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/document?repid=rep1&amp;type=pdf&amp;doi=d29523d79ffd0b6b47cb137ed480d2096d0f0e13\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\" previewlistener=\"true\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[2] <span style=\"color: black;\">Achi O.K., “Microbiology of “Obiolar”: A Nigerian Fermented Non-Alcoholic Beverage,” </span><em style=\"color: black;\">Journal of Applied Bacteriology</em><span style=\"color: black;\">, vol. 69, no. 3, pp. 321-325, </span>1990. </p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-2672.1990.tb01522.x\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\" previewlistener=\"true\">CrossRef</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Microbiology+of+%E2%80%9CObiolar%E2%80%9D.+A+Nigerian+fermented+non-alcoholic+beverage&amp;btnG=\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\" previewlistener=\"true\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a href=\"https://academic.oup.com/jambio/article-abstract/69/3/321/6725422\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\" previewlistener=\"true\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[3] Ogunbanwo Samuel Temitope, and Ogunsanya Bashirat Taiyese, “Quality Assessment of “Otika” like Beverage Produced from Pearl Millet,” <em>Journal of Applied Bioscience</em>, vol. 51, pp. 3608-3617, 2012. </p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Quality+assessment+of+%E2%80%9