(172, 7, 20, 61, 'October', 'December', 'CE-V1I1P101', '', 'Econometric Analysis of Macroeconomic Objective: Application of ARCH and GARCH Model', 1, 8, '[\"OKEOWO Idowu Adeniyi\"]', 'For macroeconomic objectives to be achieved and sustained, these objectives must be modeled together rather than isolation modeling. The main objective of this paper is to model the inflation rate, unemployment rate, exchange rate and growth rate simultaneously. The study used a time series analysis method from 1987-2022 to model macroeconomic objectives. Having observed the Autoregressive Conditional Heteroscedasticity (ARCH) effect in the data properties, the Generalised Linear Model (GLM) model was used in its estimation. All the variables contain unit roots at levels except the inflation rate. 16% increase in the inflation rate and a 7% increase in the unemployment rate bring about a 1% change in GDP. Reduction in unemployment and income inequality, encouraging small enterprises and development of rural areas are proffered as policy options. As inflation rate increases by 16%, the economy grows by 1%. In order to check the increasing rate of inflation, reduction in unnecessary government expenditure, rational wage policy, increase in production and effective price control mechanisms were equally recommended as alternative policy options. The model shows that the exchange rate depreciates as economic growth increases. To solve the problem of exchange rate misalignment, expenditure-reducing policy, import substitution, export promotion and expenditure-switching policy were recommended as viable macroeconomic policy targets.', '[\"Macroeconomic\",\"Unemployment\",\"Inflation\",\"Exchange rate\",\"Heteroscedasticity.\"]', '<p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[1] H. Adam, Economics, Corporate Finance and Accounting, Financial Analysis, 2022. [Online]. Available:<span style=\"color: black;\"> www.investopedia.com</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[2] Olivier Blanchard, Giovanni Dell’Ariccia, and Paolo Mauro, Rethinking Macroeconomic Policy, International Monetary Fund, 2010. [Online]. Available: <span style=\"color: black;\">https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/spn/2010/spn1003.PDF</span></p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[3] Laurence M. Ball, Daniel Leigh, and Prachi Mishra, “Understanding U.S. Inflation during the COVID-19 Era,” <em>National Bureau of Economic Research Working Paper Series 30613</em>, 2022.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.3386/w30613\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">CrossRef</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=%E2%80%99Understanding+US+inflation+during+the+COVID-19+era&amp;btnG=\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a href=\"https://www.nber.org/papers/w30613\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[4] Robert J. Barro, “Inflation and Economic Growth,”<em> National Bureau of Economic Research</em>, 1995.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.3386/w5326\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">CrossRef</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=Inflation+and+Economic+Growth&amp;btnG=\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Google Scholar</a>] [<a href=\"https://www.nber.org/papers/w5326\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(0, 176, 80);\">Publisher Link</a>]</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[5] Smith Christie, and Aziz Omar, “Monetary Policy Objectives-Price Stability and Macro Stabilisation,” <em>Reserve Bank of New Zealand Bulletin</em>, vol. 82, pp. 1-14, 2019.</p><p class=\"ql-align-justify\">[<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0%2C5&amp;q=%E2%80%99Mon